  "prompt": "What is the reason behind driving on the left hand side and the right hand side of the road in different countries?",
  "response": "The reasons for driving on different sides of the road have historical and cultural origins:\n\nLeft-hand driving:\n1. Originated in medieval Europe\n2. Knights were predominantly right-handed and kept their sword hand (right) free to defend against potential attacks\n3. Historically practiced by the British Empire, which spread this practice to many of its colonies\n4. Countries like India, Japan, Australia, and many African nations drive on the left\n\nRight-hand driving:\n1. Popularized by Napoleon, who influenced many European countries to switch\n2. The United States adopted right-hand driving during the early colonial period\n3. Most of continental Europe and the Americas drive on the right side\n4. Influenced by the French Revolution and subsequent Napoleon's conquests\n\nFactors influencing the choice:\n1. Colonial history\n2. Political influences\n3. Neighboring countries' practices\n4. Historical transportation methods (horse-drawn carriages)\n\nModern standardization:\n- About 35% of countries drive on the left\n- About 65% of countries drive on the right\n- Changing sides is expensive and logistically challenging, so most countries maintain their traditional side\n\nThe choice is largely historical and has remained consistent due to the significant cost and complexity of changing road infrastructure.",
